english:
  title: Record of the Hall of the Huai Moon
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Hall of the Huai Moon bears a plaque inscribed by the Buddhist monk Jinjeoljaе, yet it was named by the venerable No-hak. When Yangchon-ja inquired into its meaning, Jinjeoljae spoke thus:

    "Emptiness arises from Great Awakening, like a single bubble upon the sea. The body of Awakening pervades all places, and the nature of emptiness is nowhere absent. In every head and object, in all hues and forms—though manifold in their thousand differences—all arise from within a single Awakening. Just as one moon in the sky appears wholly in every river, and one moon upon the water illuminates each boat separately. One dwells in heaven, one in water, yet above and below merge in a single brilliance, seamless and indivisible. A boat traveling south sees the moon in the south; a boat traveling north sees the moon in the north. Yet the body of the moon itself knows neither south nor north. To call the divided reflections not the moon is incorrect; to call them the true moon is also incorrect. In the divided illuminations we seek the undivided body—thus the true moon abides within the very divisions, not as two separate things.

    Moreover, of all the waters beneath heaven, none exceed the Yangtze, the Huai, the Yellow River, and the Han. The Yellow River lies in the north; the Yangtze and Han lie in the south, while the Huai dwells between. Ascending the Huai northward, one reaches the Yellow; following the Huai southward, one reaches the Yangtze and Han. By 'the Huai's moon,' I speak of one moon dwelling at the center, its light divided between south and north. Thus lies the meaning of this hall's name. Can you set it down in words?"

    Yangchon replied: "Profound indeed is the seamlessness between water and moon! The moon dwells in heaven, water upon earth—so distant, so vast, that they should remain utterly severed, never to meet. Yet when water clarifies and moon brightens, above and below know no division. Among all things, none resonate across their kindred essences as do water and moon. For the moon is Great Yin, and water too is Great Yin. The moon waxes and wanes, while the tides rise and fall with its phases—thus water and moon share one essence. And yet they remain two distinct bodies.

    Consider: ritual water is drawn from moonlight's influence—thus water itself is born from the moon, not two from the beginning. All things that fill heaven and earth derive from a single vital force, unified by a single principle. The great cannot exceed it; the infinitesimal it does not abandon. The hidden gods cannot perceive it; the luminous humans cannot exhaust it. Above shine sun and stars; below cling grass and trees. Within, it roots in our own being; without, it encompasses all things. There is nowhere it is absent, no moment it fails. Yet its entirety converges in our heart. Therefore the heart's function penetrates the principles of things without obstruction—transcending even the relation of water and moon.

    But the moon reflected in water is but shadow, not the true moon. Here lies a distinction between water and moon. Yet the principle abiding in all things is truth without exception. Thus when the heart responds to things, it too is never without truth. Unified in one continuity, there are no divisions of above and below, inner and outer, great and minute, refined and coarse. This is why Mencius said: 'All things are complete within me. When I reflect inward with sincerity, there is no greater joy.' By sincerity is meant being true without falsehood. Human inauthenticity stems from desire's obscuring. As clouds veil the moon in heaven and mud muddies water on earth—so desire clouds our nature. Yet should we cast off desire and preserve our truth, then all things complete within us would be fully present, and the heart's wholeness would be entirely fulfilled.

    I have heard that Buddhist monks transcend worldly bonds and sever moral relations. Is this not to treat mind and the principles of things as two separate matters? Would not the body of our mind become partial, and its function incomplete? To abandon the divided reflections is to lose the true moon. Can we discard the principles of things and yet attain the heart's wholeness? The sage perfects both inner and outer, establishes both root and branch. Thus is the learning of the sage complete."

    I offered this brief summary: "The moon in water is shadow; yet the principles in all things are wholly true. Venerable teacher, I ask you to consider this carefully." Jinjeoljae replied, "Indeed, it shall be so." Thus I record this account.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Huai River (淮水) flows through central China, geographically positioned between the Yellow River (north) and the Yangtze River (south). The metaphor suggests the moon's unified nature manifesting as divided reflections—representing the relationship between absolute principle and its manifestations in particular things.
  - key: ''
    value: This dialogue presents a synthesis of Buddhist and Neo-Confucian philosophy. Jinjeoljae represents the Buddhist perspective on emptiness and non-duality, while Yangchon articulates the Neo-Confucian emphasis on principle (理) pervading all things while affirming moral engagement with the world.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'ritual water drawn from moonlight' reflects traditional East Asian cosmology in which water's capacity to reflect and transmit light connects it directly to lunar influence, symbolizing the interconnectedness of apparent opposites.
